<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>To Public Administration Select Committee</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 3pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from the Police and Crime Commissioner for Devon and Cornwall [CST0047]</span></h1><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-transform:uppercase">Crime statistics</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Please find below responses to the enquiry from the Public Administration Select Commi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ttee regarding crime statistics:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">What, if any, targets do you set for your police force? </span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For the performance year 2013/2014, the performance targets set by the Police &amp; Crime Commissioner were generally direction of travel, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">abridged from the Police &amp; Crime Plan on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the attached sheet. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Force then considered these and proposed specific numeric targets such as to reduce overall crime by -2%. These numeric targets were agreed by the PCC at a Performance &amp; Accountability Board meeting and the Chief Constable is held to account for delivery </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">against them.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">What impact do you think this has on police recording crime practices?</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Very little. I have every confidence that Devon &amp; Cornwall Police adheres to highly ethical and stringent crime recording practices and it is anticipated that this will b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e reflected in the forthcoming HMIC inspection on data integrity. However increased scrutiny of performance in relation to targets has caused the Force to critically evaluate how recording practices may be affecting relative performance. In this respect th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e Force has identified an area of business where it is believed that the Force may be over zealous in their recording practices and external independent validation of this has been sought. </span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">How do you assure yourself that the recorded crime figures for your area are correct? </span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are a number of internal and external points of reference that are available to reality check our crime figures. These include the Crime Survey for England &amp; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wales, HMIC Value for Money Profiles, Crime Comparator and Inspection reports and internal audits of NCRS and NSIR compliance. In addition the PCC holds Performance and Accountability Board meetings monthly where the crime trends are examined in detail and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the Chief Constable required to provide evidence to explain the current trend or position. Finally the Police &amp; Crime Commissioner, the Chief Constable and senior leaders within the Force clearly communicate uncompromising messages about recording integri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ty both internally among officers and staff and to the public at large.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To what extent can you trust the crime statistics for your area? </span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 48.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As stated above I hav</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e a strong degree of confidence in the accuracy of the crime statistics for our area. This can b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e verified through internal audit and compliance and external HMIC inspections. </span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The focus on data accuracy and integrity only addresses one part of the issue surrounding how confident the public and policy makers can be that crime statistics can be relied</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on. The unasked question seems to be whether data can be compared between forces with confidence (i.e. is the data reliable). The answer to this is almost certainly not. There is a degree of flexibility in the system currently that even when recording in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">accordance with the guidance set out in the National Crime Recording Standards and within agreed time frames there are significant differences in the resulting data. In addition how each force interprets the NCRS can vary slightly but significantly, for ex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ample the line between anti-social behaviour (a non-crime incident), public disorder (an offence against society) and low level violence (a victim-based crime) is particularly blurred. What is needed to address this is a means of measuring more reliably, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd accounting for, variability in compliance and recording between forces. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Minion Pro'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">How I will measure success and hold the Chief Constable to account </span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:487.3pt"><tr style="height:5.6pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:232.2pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p></td><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:255.1pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Measure </span></p></td></tr><tr style="height:47pt"><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padd